}}\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa326\partightenfactor0
\cf4 And the mean-- which is where the dot plot balances-- is nearly twice as big, at $77,000. This mean doesn't represent the common experience. Only 27% of these incomes fall above $77,000, with 73% below them. So which measure of centre should we use? That depends on what we want to use it for. For incomes, and many highly-skewed variables, the median tends to be preferable because it better represents the common experience, or what is typical. Half of the people get less. Half get more. Finally, I'll leave you with these questions, to remind you of the ideas we've just covered.\
